1490":"circa 1490","1506":"1506","after 1520":"na 1520","1516":"1516","Genderen, Noord-Brabant, Nederland":"Genderen, Noord-Brabant, Nederland","North Brabant, Netherlands":"Noord-Brabant, Nederland"},"en":{"Abt 1490–Bef 1587":"about 1490–before about 1587","1490–1587":"1490–1587","1500–1520":"1500–1520","1520–1587":"1520–1587","1470–Male":"1470–Deceased","before 1587":"before 1587","1572":"1572","Bef 1587":"before about 1587","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","1579":"1579","1500":"1500","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","about 1520":"about 1520","Abt 1490":"about 1490","1506":"1506","after 1520":"after 1520","1516":"1516","Genderen, Noord-Brabant, Nederland":"Genderen, North Brabant, Netherlands","North Brabant, Netherlands":"North Brabant, Netherlands","nameMeanings":[{"name":"van","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Anh, Thanh, Hung, Minh, Vinh, Dung, Hue, Huong, Lan, Quang, Tan, Thuy, Hong, Chi, Hang, Ho, Pok, Sang, Bai, Chin, Ching, Chu, Chuan, Dong.","Vietnamese (<b>Vạn</b>): from the Chinese surname 萬, see   Wan   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Văn</b>): from the Chinese surnames 文 or 聞, see   Wen   2 and 3, and also 5 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Wan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Yi, Qi, Qiang, Wai, Yiu, Yuk, Chien-Min, Fang, Hin, Jichun, Li, Man, Chung, Min, Yiping, Pak, Sik, Sung Man.  Vietnamese Tin, Bang, Da, Hien, Hoi, Lan, Minh Quang, Sau, Tich, Tung, Yaping, Yuet.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 萬, which means ‘ten thousand’ literally or ‘very great number’ figuratively: (i) from the personal name of Bi Wan (畢萬), an official in the state of Jin (located in present-day Shanxi province). He was said to be a descendant of Bi Gong Gao (known as Duke of Bi), the 15th son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (reined 1152–1056  BC ). Bi Wan was later granted the fiefdom of Wei (魏), which in 403  BC  became the state of Wei (located in present-day Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan and Hebei provinces). Some of his descendants adopted Wei (魏) as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his personal name, as their surname. (ii) from the personal name Wan (萬), style name of Rui Bo (芮伯, the Earl of Rui), an official of the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), who was granted the fief Rui (located in Ruicheng in Shaanxi province). Some of his descendants inherited Rui (芮), the name of the fief, as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his style name, as their surname. (iii) from the placename Wan (萬), the name of a fief (located in Juxian in Shandong province) granted during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) to an official in the ancient state of Chu. (iv) from the first element of the name of the Wan Si (萬俟) family, who lived in the downstream areas of the Yellow River during the Northern Qi dynasty (550–577  AD ). (v) from the second element of the name of the Tu Wan (吐萬) family, who are members of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 完, meaning ‘complete’ in Chinese: (i) said to be borne by the descendants of Huan Zhui, a grandson of the Duke Huan of Song (ruler of the state of Song, died 651  BC ). (ii) from Wan (完), the name of Qu Wan (屈完), an official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn Period (770–476  BC ). (iii) shortened form of the compound surname Wan-Yan (完顔), a surname from minority ethnic groups such as Juchen ethnic group in ancient northern China."]}]},{"name":"der","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Zoltan, Istvan, Janos, Lajos.","Hungarian (<b>Dér</b>): from the old personal name <i>Dér</i> of Turkic origin, or a nickname for a gray-haired man, from the vocabulary word <i>dér</i> ‘hoarfrost’.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 謝, see   Xie   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Xie","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Hong, Li, Ming, Ying, Min, Qing, Yuan, Bin, Hui, Ping, Wei, Xiaoli, Ding, Chang, Lan, Quan, Cong, Dang, Hai, Tian, Yiping.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 謝, meaning ‘thank’ in Chinese: (i) from Xie (謝), the name of an ancient state (possibly located in Nanyang in Henan province), annexed around the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ).Later this place was probably granted to Shen Bo (the Earl of Shen), uncle of King Xuan of Zhou (reigned 827–782  BC ). After it was annexed during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), the name of the state was adopted as a surname. (ii) adopted in place of the surname Zhi-Le (直勒) by Xie Xiaozheng (謝孝政), an official during the Northern Qi dynasty (550–577  AD )."]}]},{"name":"Dussen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from the genitive form of   Busse   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Bussan","meanings":["Americanized form of an unidentified German surname, most likely   Bussen  .","History: Felix Bussan, born in Germany, arrived in New York in 1897, on board the <i>Normannia</i>. Willy Bussan, born in Germany, left Hamburg on board the <i>Deutschland</i> and arrived in New York in 1907."]},{"name":"Busse","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ewald, Ernst, Fritz, Konrad, Claus, Eberhard, Eckhard, Frieda, Fritzi, Gerhard, Helmuth.","German: variant of   Buss  . This surname is also found in Poland. Compare   Bussey  .","North German (<b>Büsse</b>): metonymic occupational name for a maker of boxes and containers or for a gunsmith, from Middle Low German <i>büsse</i>, <i>busse</i> ‘box, gun, rifle’."]}]},{"name":"Barend","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Filipino: from Ilokano <i>bareng</i> ‘hope’, a nickname denoting a hopeful person."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Pietersz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Raymonde, Laurent, Marcel, Pierre, Serge.  Dutch Bernardus, Wim, Bram, Pieter, Willem.","Dutch and Flemish: patronymic from the personal name <i>Pieter</i> (see   Peter  ). This surname is also found in Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Peter","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1356696,"age":16,"year":"1506","julianDay":2271115,"description":"The Netherlands is inherited by the future Habsburg Emperor and King of Spain Charles V.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1356697,"age":26,"year":"1516","julianDay":2274767,"description":"The Catholic King Charles I of Spain ruled the Netherlands.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1356698,"age":82,"year":"1572","julianDay":2295221,"description":"William of Orange was recognized as viceroy of Holland, Friesland and Utrecht.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":3839489,"age":89,"year":"1579","julianDay":2297778,"description":"After the signing of the Treaty of Utrecht in 1579, Brabant became a regular battlefield between the Republic of the Netherlands (Protestant) and Spain (Catholic).","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Barend Pietersz van der Dussen was born about 1490, in Genderen, North Brabant, Netherlands as the son 